Catastrophic failure of the acetabular component in a ceramic-polyethylene 
bearing total hip arthroplasty.

Simon JA(1), Dayan AJ, Ergas E, Stuchin SA, Di Cesare PE.

Author information:
(1)Hospital for Joint Diseases, New York, New York 10003, USA.

Recent research in total hip arthroplasty has focused on attempts to decrease 
wear at the femoral head-acetabulum articulation, to limit the production of 
debris that is believed to lead to osteolysis and prosthetic loosening. The use 
of ceramic-on-polyethylene bearing surfaces has been reported to produce lower 
wear rates and therefore may increase the life expectancy of the joint 
arthroplasty. Problems with this bearing have been reported to be due to ceramic 
femoral head fracture. Reported here are 2 cases of catastrophic failure of 
total hip arthroplasties, involving a ceramic femoral head, caused by failure of 
the polyethylene acetabular liner, with subsequent penetration of the femoral 
head through the acetabular shell.

